   "hider_text": "The wood is cool beneath my palm, not cold—like the skin of an old friend. It holds the weight of silence, not emptiness. I press my fingers into the grain, and it shivers, not with sound, but with memory. There’s a seam at the edge where the varnish cracked once, thin as breath, and when I touch it, it remembers the warmth of / The wind hums through the old iron fence at the edge of the garden, not loud, but persistent — like a breath held too long. The gate creaks when stirred, not by wind, but by movement behind it. There’s a patch of moss where the stones meet the ground, and it’s not green — it’s a dull, grayish velvet that seems to drink light. / The wind moves through the tall, thin fingers of the dunes—dry, slow, like breath taken through a cracked mouth. It doesn’t carry words, only the sound of something old shifting beneath the surface.  \n\nSunlight slants across the cracked earth, not golden, but sharp, like old glass cut too deep. The color isn’t warm—it’s a kind of flat, exposed white",
   "seeker_text": "The smell of wet earth after rain.  \n\nNot the kind you find in gardens or parks, but the deep, slow seep of it beneath a cracked sidewalk in the middle of winter, where snow has melted too slowly to form puddles, only to freeze again at the edges. It’s not sweet, not sharp—just a quiet presence, like the world is breathing through the ground. I / The scent of wet earth after rain.  \nNot the smell of soil, not the smell of roots — but the way it rises from the garden path where someone has just walked, carrying their boots through the damp, leaving a trail of cold, green breath. I remember it from the edge of a summer dusk, when the air was thick with the quiet hum of crickets and the distant creak / The sound of rain on the roof.  \nNot the kind that drums like a heartbeat, but the soft, steady *drip-drip* of a single drop finding its way down the eaves. It happens once every few minutes, like a slow blink. I don’t know if it’s from the roof above or the one below—the house I’m in is old and the walls breathe."
  },
